        <name>14.4.2.1 Area of surface</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Find the area of the surface generated when the part of the curve \(y=x^3\) between \(x=0\) and \(x=4\) is rotated around the \(x\) axis.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using the previous Key Point, write down the integral:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
    &lt;tbody&gt;
        &lt;tr&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;\(\displaystyle \int\)&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;
                &lt;table&gt;
                    &lt;tbody&gt;
                        &lt;tr&gt;
                            &lt;td&gt;[[input:ans1up]] [[validation:ans1up]]&lt;/td&gt;
                        &lt;/tr&gt;
                        &lt;tr&gt;
                            &lt;td&gt;[[input:ans1dn]] [[validation:ans1dn]]&lt;/td&gt;
                        &lt;/tr&gt;
                    &lt;/tbody&gt;
                &lt;/table&gt;
            &lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt; [[input:ans1int]] \(\mathrm{d}x\) [[validation:ans1int]]&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use the substitution \(u=1+9x^4\) so \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}u}{\mathrm{d}x}=36 x^3\) to write down the integral in terms of \(u\):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
    &lt;tbody&gt;
        &lt;tr&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;\(\displaystyle \int\)&lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt;
                &lt;table&gt;
                    &lt;tbody&gt;
                        &lt;tr&gt;
                            &lt;td&gt;[[input:ans2up]] [[validation:ans2up]]&lt;/td&gt;
                        &lt;/tr&gt;
                        &lt;tr&gt;
                            &lt;td&gt;[[input:ans2dn]] [[validation:ans2dn]]&lt;/td&gt;
                        &lt;/tr&gt;
                    &lt;/tbody&gt;
                &lt;/table&gt;
            &lt;/td&gt;
            &lt;td&gt; [[input:ans2int]] \(\mathrm{d}u\) [[validation:ans2int]]&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Perform the integration and apply the limits of integration to find the area, giving your answer in &lt;b&gt;exact form.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[input:ans3]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;\[\text{area}=\int_a^b 2\pi y \sqrt{1+\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)^2} \ \mathrm{d}x= \int_0^4 2 \pi x^3 \sqrt{1+(3x^2)^2} \ \mathrm{d}x = \int_0^4 2 \pi x^3 \sqrt{1+9x^4} \ \mathrm{d}x\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using the substitution \(u=1+9x^4\), we calculate that the upper limit is \(u=1+9(4)^4=2305\), and the lower limit is \(u=1+9(0)^4=1\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the integral becomes \[A = \int_1^{2305} 2 \pi x^3 \sqrt{u} \frac{\mathrm{d}u}{36x^3} = \frac{\pi}{18}\int_1^{2305} \sqrt{u}\ \mathrm{d}u\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Performing the integration, we obtain \[\frac{\pi}{18} \left[\frac{2 u^{\frac{3}{3}}}{3}\right]^{2305}_1\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Applying the limits of integration, the area is calculated to be: \(A = \dfrac{\pi}{27}\left((2305)^{\frac{3}{2}}-1\right).\)&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
